24.You rename a resource from aws_instance.app to aws_instance.web_app in your configuration but forget to add a moved block. What will happen when you run terraform apply?
When you rename a resource in your Terraform configuration without using a moved block, Terraform treats this as two separate operations: removing the old resource and adding a
new resource. Terraform compares your configuration against the state file and sees that aws_instance.app no longer exists in your code (plans to destroy it) and
aws_instance.web_app is a new resource (plans to create it). This results in your infrastructure being destroyed and recreated, causing downtime and potential data loss.

25. You want HCP Terraform to automatically detect when someone manually modifies a resource outside of Terraform. Which feature should you enable?
HCP Terraform health assessments automatically monitor your managed infrastructure and detect when real-world resources no longer match your Terraform configuration.
Once enabled, health assessments run approximately every 24 hours and include two types of evaluations: drift detection (compares actual infrastructure against the state file) 
and continuous validation (checks whether custom conditions like check blocks, preconditions, and postconditions still pass). Health assessments are available in HCP 
Terraform Standard and Premium editions.

26. How should you reference the connection_string output from a child module named database in the root module?
module.database.connection_string
To access output values from a child module, you use the syntax module.MODULE_NAME.OUTPUT_NAME. You cannot directly reference resources defined inside a module from outside
that module — the module boundary enforces encapsulation, and outputs are the interface for exposing data. Note that even though the output is marked as sensitive = true, 
you can still reference it in your configuration — Terraform will just redact it from logs and plan output.

